===subject:Approaches
===from:Arlo Hanlin Hemphill
===email:ahemphil@nova.edu
===institution_site:http://www.nova.edu/ocean
===institution:NSUOC
===date:Tue Feb 18 11:56:12 2003
===message:Michelle,

Sometimes I wonder if it might not be better to make all regulations in these areas tougher than they need to be.  For example, make all hunting illegal in huge reserve areas.  In reality, many species could probably be sustainably hunted.  Since the people are going to do it anyway, make it entirely illegal and maybe the end product will be the sustainable level you hoped for in the first place?  I doubt it, but it might be something to look into.

Arlo


=========yorg=========
===subject:enforcement
===from:Michelle
===date:Fri Mar  7 11:14:40 2003
===message:I had thought of that-- but I think the problem remains with enforcement. If you make hunting totally illegal in an area, you need to up the enforcement, ie have rangers at all entrances, ensuring visitors do not enter with firearms, etc... It almost seems as if this would not do any good, considering these issues. 
